This line:

    role = JOptionPane.showInputDialog(&quot;Please enter your name&quot;);

Will **never** throw an exception as is, because `showInputDialog(&quot;...&quot;)` returns a **string**. Therefore, even if the user enters `42`, the value you get is the **string** `&quot;42&quot;`.

Now to check whether the string is an integer, one way of doing so is using a regular expression:

    if(role.matches(&quot;-?\\d+&quot;)) {
        throw new InputMismatchException(); //throw your exception
    }

However, like others mentioned in the comments, why would you throw an exception and then handle it in the `catch` block? You could directly display an error message from inside the above `if` statement like so, without throwing any exception:

    if(role.matches(&quot;-?\\d+&quot;)) {
        JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(null, &quot;Invalid Input&quot;, &quot;&quot;,JOptionPane.PLAIN_MESSAGE);
    }

